## 📝 Interview Questions

**Q1. How do you prevent a form from submitting and refreshing the page?**
> Call `event.preventDefault()` inside the `submit` event listener. This stops the default browser behavior of sending the form and refreshing.

**Q2. What is `FormData` and when would you use it?**
> `FormData` automatically collects all form fields into key-value pairs. It's used to easily build form submissions including file uploads, and can be sent directly as `fetch` body without JSON serialization.

**Q3. What is debouncing and where would you use it?**
> Debouncing delays a function execution until after a pause in calls. If calls keep coming, the timer resets. Used for search inputs, window resize handlers, and form validation — preventing unnecessary API calls on every keystroke.

**Q4. What is the difference between debouncing and throttling?**
> Debouncing waits until calls stop and runs once after the pause. Throttling runs at most once per interval regardless of how many calls come in. Debounce = "run after user finishes"; Throttle = "run at most every X ms".

**Q5. What is a DocumentFragment and why is it useful?**
> It's a lightweight in-memory DOM container. You build your elements inside it without affecting the live DOM, then append it in one operation — causing only one reflow/repaint. Better performance than appending elements one by one.

**Q6. What is IntersectionObserver and what is it used for?**
> An API that notifies when an element enters or leaves the viewport. Used for lazy loading images, triggering animations when elements scroll into view, and infinite scroll pagination — without expensive scroll event listeners.

**Q7. What is layout thrashing and how do you avoid it?**
> Layout thrashing happens when you alternate between reading layout properties (like `offsetHeight`) and writing styles in a loop — forcing the browser to recalculate layout repeatedly. Avoid it by batching all reads first, then all writes.

